layout.tsx — Root layout that loads the Geist and Geist Mono fonts from next/font/google as CSS variables, imports the site-wide css, sets the window title metadata to "fran++ v0.0.5" with the description "Human to free-text context to Python", and renders the html and body elements as a full-height flex column with antialiasing.

globals.css — Global stylesheet: imports tailwindcss, defines the dark palette as CSS variables (#09090b background, #f4f4f5 foreground, plus the fp-ground/surface/hairline/text/text-muted/text-dim/accent/accent-soft tokens), maps them into an inline @theme block along with the font variables, applies border-box sizing, min-height and background/foreground colors to html and body, Arial as the body font, pointer and not-allowed cursors for buttons, full-height rules for the codemirror merge view, rounded button-pill classes (.btn, .btn-secondary, .btn-danger, .btn-primary) with hover states, and the icon action row plus .icon-btn/.icon-btn-danger/.icon-btn-primary variants that render a masked .icon-mask span from a --icon-url variable.

page.tsx — The main editor page, a client component that drives the whole .human to .context to .py pipeline for the active program against the backend.
Keeps the saved workspace (human/context/python text, compiled split units, active hashes, status flags, context role, provenance entries, history tree) plus per-kind editable drafts, and merges fresh server responses into unchanged drafts while preserving in-flight edits.
Auto-adopts the moment a files response arrives seeded, swapping it for the adopted response before it lands in the workspace, sending adopt errors to the status bar without wiping the seeded texts, and letting a click on the same still-seeded program re-load and retry the adoption instead of just switching tabs.
Renders a tab strip: one pipeline tab per visible kind (name.human always, name.context only when a non-direct context snapshot exists, name.py only when there are no split units), one editable code tab per compiled split unit whose per-target draft is stored with the unit's hash and discarded the moment that hash changes, and one editable plain tab per arbitrary workspace file opened from the sidebar; every tab shows a glyph by extension, a dirty dot, and a close button, closing falls back to the next sensible tab, and tab labels show just the file's basename, picking up a parent-folder or program-name suffix when two open tabs share a basename.
Wires the sidebar file browser: program names come from the file's path relative to the sidebar's tree root with forward slashes, one leading human/ segment stripped, and the extension removed — so human/backend/backend.human loads the program backend/backend whether the tree root is the workspace or the human folder itself, and human/fifth.human loads fifth; a click only routes into program loading when the file browser reports the file is paired with a .human sibling, every other entry opens as a plain tab read through the fs api under its own full path, and a click on a file whose relative path — with one leading project/ segment stripped, symmetrically — matches a compiled split unit's target opens that unit tab, keeping a backend main.py and a root main.py distinct.
Newly created entries adopt their content into the matching kind, and delete requests raise the shared confirmation modal before calling the fs delete endpoint, pruning any plain tabs under the removed path, hiding the pipeline kind whose relative program path matches the open program, and closing the unit tab whose split target resolves to the deleted path under the same project/ strip.
Below the browser sits a history panel for the current program: a collapsible tree of .human snapshots with their child contexts and pythons, short hashes, leaf/split/direct role badges, missing-node markers, per-flow copy that fetches the full bundle, a copy-program shortcut, and checkout of any snapshot which replaces the workspace and highlights the lines belonging to the picked target.
Action buttons per tab: copy to clipboard everywhere, a sparkles compile on the .human tab that runs the full compile endpoint, and a sparkles compile on the .context tab that runs context-to-python; pending panes cover the gaps — save-the-parent prompts when an upstream draft is dirty, a generate human-to-context prompt when no context exists for the snapshot, a direct-role notice when the compiler skipped .context, and a generate prompt when no .py exists yet.
Next to each sparkles compile sits a compact dark-styled select pill choosing the compile target language (python, typescript, tsx, javascript, css, json, html, markdown); the choice is threaded as the language argument into every compile, context-to-python, and human-to-context call, defaults to python, and is persisted under the localStorage key franpp.compile-language, restored on mount when the stored value is one of the known languages.
Saving: Ctrl+S routes to the program save endpoint for the selected kind, saveUnit for a dirty unit tab, or the fs write endpoint for a plain tab, and unit tabs also get a save button beside copy enabled only while the unit is dirty; a dirty pipeline kind renders a split view with the editable draft beside a diff of the saved snapshot.
Provenance tracing: while ctrl/meta is held, .human phrases cited in the provenance entries and .context lines that link onward are highlighted as clickable ranges; ctrl-click on a human phrase resolves the narrowest matching phrase occurrence to its cited lines and jumps to .context (or straight to .py when the context role is direct), ctrl-click on a context line jumps to the mapped .py lines or opens the owning split unit's real code tab through the file-tree unit machinery (focusing it if already open) with the mapped code lines highlighted — preferring provenance entries whose contextLine equals the clicked line and falling back to phrase-intersection matching, and ctrl-right-click on a human phrase opens a reword popover that rebinds the same compiled output to the new wording through the reword endpoint without recompiling, with a friendly error if the endpoint is missing; whenever unsaved edits make line numbers drift, every affordance re-resolves its entries by stripped-text match against the current buffer, preferring the occurrence nearest the recorded line number, and keeps the fast path of trusting recorded numbers untouched while the buffer still equals the saved text.
A footer status bar shows the last message or error, the context role badge, and the short hash of the active snapshot; failed mutating calls also raise a dismissible red error banner overlaying the top of the editor, showing the backend's detail string until its close button clears it; on mount the page fetches the project list and bounces to the picker when no project is active.

projects/page.tsx — The projects list: fetches all projects on mount and renders them as rows with an active-accent bar, the project name, a "last compiled" time-ago column, and a trash control that raises the shared confirmation modal warning that the project and all its .human/.context/.py snapshots go away; clicking or keyboard-activating a row selects that project on the backend and routes to the root screen; an inline form creates a new project from a typed name, an "Open folder" control asks the backend to show a native folder dialog and routes home with the picked path as a query param, and busy/error states gate every control.

explorer/page.tsx — A tiny server component for the explorer route that just redirects to the home page, preserving an optional path search param as ?path= on the destination.
